<div id="review_1177703521" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1177703521" />
    <a title="Alex" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3144945-alex"><img alt="Alex" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1594856152p2/3144945.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1177703521?book_show_action=true">Jan 23, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex" href="/user/show/3144945-alex">Alex</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3144945-alex?shelf=historical-literary-fiction">historical-literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3144945-alex?shelf=2016">2016</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1177703521" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10147777248840362673">Here&apos;s a sprawling behemoth of a love letter to Victorian novels. Like Sarah Waters&apos; <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/752091050' title='My review' rel='nofollow noopener'>Tipping the Velvet</a> and John Fowles&apos; <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/809335547' title='my review' rel='nofollow noopener'>The French Lieutenant&apos;s Woman,</a> it gets a charge out of paying homage to Victorian tropes while undermining them: Victorian novels were famously prudish, so Faber gives us descriptions of the toxic prophylactic methods of Victorian prostitutes. This is all good fun.<br/><br/>The gothic and sensation genres are Faber&apos;s main touchstones here. Sugar&apos;s stint as an infiltrating governess reca</span>
  <span id="freeText10147777248840362673" style="display:none">Here's a sprawling behemoth of a love letter to Victorian novels. Like Sarah Waters' <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/752091050" title="My review" rel="nofollow noopener">Tipping the Velvet</a> and John Fowles' <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/809335547" title="my review" rel="nofollow noopener">The French Lieutenant's Woman,</a> it gets a charge out of paying homage to Victorian tropes while undermining them: Victorian novels were famously prudish, so Faber gives us descriptions of the toxic prophylactic methods of Victorian prostitutes. This is all good fun.<br /><br />The gothic and sensation genres are Faber's main touchstones here. Sugar's stint as an infiltrating governess recalls <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/177295526" title="My review" rel="nofollow noopener">Lady Audley's Secret</a> (as well as a whole group of less remembered <a href="http://www.victorianweb.org/gender/wadso2.html" title="Article on Victorian Web" rel="nofollow noopener">governess novels</a>). Faber gets his <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/190831963" title="My review of Woman in White" rel="nofollow noopener">Wilkie Collins</a> on, too, as we get a peek into Agnes Rackham's diaries.<br /><br />Unfortunately, it's not as good as The Woman in White: Agnes' diary is way more boring than Marian's, and we're short a Fosco. The second half of this 800+-page tome gets a little slow. I waited for Henry Rackham's story to get interesting - I just assumed it was a matter of time before he started <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[murdering hookers <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> - but he never got around to it. Sugar, left in charge of William's neglected daughter Sophie, ends up exchanging <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[prostitution for child-rearing, <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> which is way more boring. You'll have some degree of fun with this if you like Victorian novels - it's fun to watch Faber take them apart and put them back together - but it didn't leave me with a deep impression.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10147777248840362673" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


